[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2-12 per active member per month (depends on care-journey complexity, integration depth, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, and human-care-manager backstop sizing)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret is 71. Three weeks ago she fell in her kitchen, cracked the radius in her left wrist, and spent eight hours in the emergency department of a hospital that is in-network for her Medicare Advantage plan but is not the hospital her primary care physician practices at. She was sent home with a splint, a prescription for hydrocodone, a stack of discharge papers, and instructions to follow up with an orthopedist within seven to ten days. The orthopedist on the discharge paperwork was a name and a phone number Margaret had never heard of, on the other side of town, and (she discovered three days later when she finally got through to a human at that office) booked out about six weeks. The receptionist at the orthopedist's office told Margaret to call her PCP for a referral to someone else. Margaret called her PCP. The PCP's office told Margaret they would put in a referral, but it would take two to three days to process, and that the orthopedist she got matched to would depend on her insurance, and that Margaret should call back if she had not heard within a week. Five days later, Margaret had not heard. Margaret called the PCP's office. The receptionist said the referral had been submitted but they did not have visibility into when the orthopedist's office would call. Margaret should call the orthopedist's office. Margaret asked which orthopedist. The receptionist read the name out. Margaret called the orthopedist. They had no record of the referral. Margaret called the PCP's office back. The PCP's office said they had received an electronic acknowledgment but if the orthopedist did not have it, Margaret should ask them to look again. Margaret started crying.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret has Medicare Advantage. She has a copay for specialist visits. She also has, since the fall, a list of seventeen things that are pending in her care: the orthopedic follow-up that has not been scheduled; the physical therapy that the orthopedist will need to order once she has been seen; the pain medication, which is running low and which she is not sure whether to refill because she does not know if she is supposed to keep taking it; the bone-density scan her PCP mentioned three months ago that she has not gotten around to scheduling; the mammogram she is overdue for; the eye exam she is overdue for; the diabetic foot check she is overdue for; the recheck on the A1c that was 7.6 last time; the medication reconciliation she meant to talk to her pharmacist about; the home safety evaluation her daughter has been asking about ever since the fall; the question of whether she should be on a bisphosphonate now; the question of whether her cholesterol medication is interacting with the new pain medication; the followup with cardiology she was supposed to schedule last spring; the open question with her insurance company about whether the ER visit is going to be covered; the open prior auth for a sleep study her PCP ordered eight weeks ago that she has heard nothing about; the open question of whether she should drive to her granddaughter's birthday party next weekend with her wrist still in a splint; and the slowly-rising sense that she is failing at being a person, because the work of managing her own healthcare has become a full-time job that she does not have a job description for, training for, or, increasingly, energy for.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret's daughter, who lives four states away and who is herself a healthcare worker (a hospital social worker; she knows how this is supposed to go), spent two hours on the phone with Margaret last weekend trying to triage the list. The daughter made a spreadsheet. The spreadsheet has columns for "what," "who's responsible," "what's the next step," "what's the deadline," and "what happens if it doesn't get done." Eight of the seventeen rows have, in the "who's responsible" column, the answer "Mom." Three of the rows have "I'll do it for her." The remaining six have "unclear." The daughter is going to fly out next month and try to clear the backlog in person. She is dreading it. She loves her mother. She also has a job, two kids, a life. She is angry with the healthcare system for delivering, in lieu of care coordination, this particular flavor of unpaid family labor. She is right to be angry.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the central problem of care coordination in the United States in 2026, and it is one of the largest sources of avoidable cost, avoidable harm, and avoidable patient suffering in the entire healthcare system. The clinical knowledge for managing Margaret's care is not in dispute. Her PCP knows what should happen. The orthopedist, when she eventually sees one, will know what should happen. The endocrinologist who manages her diabetes knows what should happen. The cardiologist she has not seen in fifteen months knows what should happen. The pharmacist knows what should happen. The institutional care management team, if they were to look at Margaret's chart, would have a precise list of what should happen. The reason what should happen is not happening is not a clinical-knowledge problem. It is a coordination problem. Twenty-something pending items, distributed across six or seven entities (PCP office, orthopedist's office, physical therapy, the hospital that did the ED visit, the imaging center, the pharmacy, the insurance company, the patient herself, the patient's daughter), each with their own systems, their own queues, their own staffing realities, and their own incentives, are not being orchestrated by anyone. The default coordinator is the patient. The patient, in this case, is 71, has a fractured wrist, is in pain, is exhausted, and is at the limit of what she can hold in her head.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical discipline, is the work of holding the longitudinal model of the patient's care, tracking the open items, closing the loops, surfacing the gaps, escalating the stuck items, and ensuring that what was supposed to happen actually happens. Done well by humans, it transforms outcomes. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for care coordination interventions is documented in studies including those from the Care Transitions Intervention (Coleman et al.), the Geriatric Resources for Assessment and Care of Elders (GRACE) program, the Camden Coalition, transitions of care research from CMS, and ongoing work in primary care medical home models; specific outcome figures vary by program and population --> Patients with active care management spend less time in the hospital, have fewer ED visits, have better adherence, have better-controlled chronic conditions, and report substantially better experiences with their care. Done well, care coordination is one of the highest-leverage interventions in healthcare. The reason most patients do not have it is, again, structural. Care coordination is human-labor-intensive, the people who do it well (registered nurses, social workers, community health workers) are scarce and expensive, and the U.S. fee-for-service payment system has historically not paid for it. Even in capitated payment models where care coordination is paid for, the staffing and the operational scale required to deliver it to the broad population are enormous. Most institutions reach a few percent of their attributed lives with formal care coordination; the other 95% are left to navigate the system on their own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generation of digital care-coordination products tried to address this with portals and apps. The patient could log into a portal, see a list of upcoming appointments, send a message to the care team, view some lab results, and do a few transactional tasks. These tools improved the patient experience for the patients who used them, which was a smaller fraction than expected, particularly among the patients with the highest care complexity and the lowest digital comfort. <!-- TODO: verify; patient portal adoption rates have continued to climb but remain uneven, with substantially lower adoption among older adults, lower-income patients, patients with limited English proficiency, patients without consistent internet access, and patients with cognitive impairment; specific figures vary by health system and patient population --> The portals were also, fundamentally, view-and-message tools, not coordination tools. The portal could show the patient the list of seventeen things; the portal could not actually coordinate them. The patient was still the coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2023 and continuing forward, is that conversational AI got good enough to take some of the actual coordination work, not just the visibility-into-the-list work. A patient asking a chat tool "where is my orthopedic referral" can, in the right product design, get an answer that includes (a) which specialist the referral was sent to, (b) what the status is, (c) when the patient should expect to be contacted, (d) what to do if the patient is not contacted by that date, and (e) a button that escalates to a human care navigator if the patient wants help moving the referral forward. A patient asking "what is supposed to happen next" can get a personalized list pulled from the patient's actual care plan, with each item annotated with status, the next step, and the expected timeline. A patient asking "I'm overwhelmed, can someone help me" can get connected to a human care navigator with the conversation context attached, instead of being told to leave a voicemail and wait to be called back.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot is not a care manager. The bot does not replace the registered nurse who knows the institutional referral pathways inside out. The bot is, in the right product design, a coordination tool that takes some of the visibility, some of the loop-closing, some of the gap-surfacing, and some of the escalation work that the patient was previously doing alone, and runs it on infrastructure that does not get tired at 9 PM, does not have a panel size, and does not put a patient on hold. The human care management team is still there for the cases that need them. The bot extends their reach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that bot. The care coordination assistant is the conversational AI use case where the architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes (FAQ bot, scheduling, refills, intake, benefits navigator, triage, chronic disease coach, mental health support) all converge into a single longitudinal multi-system multi-episode product, and where several patterns inherited from the chronic disease coach (longitudinal memory, care plan grounding, escalation pathways) extend across an even broader integration surface (referral systems, prior auth systems, scheduling systems across multiple practices, hospital discharge systems, post-acute care facilities, home health, durable medical equipment, pharmacy, transportation, social services, community resources). The care coordination assistant is, in some sense, the integration recipe of the chapter; the conversational core is recognizable, but the value lives almost entirely in the coordination work the bot can actually accomplish on the patient's behalf, which depends on the depth and quality of the integrations available to it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that helps a patient navigate complex multi-provider care: tracking referrals across the loop (placed, accepted, scheduled, completed, results back, plan updated), coordinating between specialists (the patient sees endocrinology, cardiology, nephrology, and primary care; the bot helps the patient understand what each is doing and how the pieces fit), managing care transitions (hospital discharge to home, post-acute facility to home, primary care to specialist, specialist to specialist, ED visit to primary care follow-up), surfacing gaps (overdue preventive care, overdue chronic-disease monitoring, open prior auths, stuck referrals), helping the patient plan the next steps (what is supposed to happen, when, who is responsible, what to do if it does not happen on time), connecting to ancillary services (transportation to appointments, durable medical equipment, home health, social services, community resources), and warm-handing-off to a human care navigator when the situation calls for one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. The care coordination assistant handles the navigation and orchestration work for established care; when a patient surfaces an acute concern (chest pain, severe shortness of breath, sudden neurological symptoms, mental-health crisis), the assistant hands off to triage workflows or to direct emergency routing. The coordination assistant does not try to do triage from scratch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease management coach. Recipe 11.7 covers ongoing chronic-disease coaching. The two recipes can coexist (and often do) in the same patient's care; the coach is condition-specific (helping the patient manage their diabetes), and the coordination assistant is whole-care-plan-specific (helping the patient navigate all the moving parts across all of their conditions). The two share consent-gated context where appropriate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a mental health support bot. Recipe 11.8 covers conversational mental-health support. When a patient surfaces mental-health concerns during a coordination conversation, the assistant routes per the institutional crisis-pathway and care-team-availability policies; the deep mental-health-specific architecture lives in 11.8.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a benefits navigator. Recipe 11.5 covers insurance benefits navigation. Coordination conversations frequently surface benefits questions (is this referral in network, what will the copay be, will my insurance cover the post-acute facility, what do I do about this denied prior auth); the coordination assistant routes those to the benefits navigator's infrastructure rather than reinventing it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a primary care doctor. The recommendations the assistant makes (here is what is supposed to happen next, here is who you should follow up with, here is what your care plan says about this) are grounded in the patient's actual signed care plan and the institution's clinical guidelines. The assistant does not invent care plans; the assistant operates on the care plan the clinical team has authored.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for human care management. The human care management team is still the backstop. The bot extends their reach to the broad population that human care management cannot serve at scale; the human team focuses where their judgment is most needed (high-complexity patients, escalations, situations the bot cannot reasonably handle).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not one product. Care coordination needs vary substantially by patient population. The needs of an oncology patient mid-treatment are different from the needs of a Medicare patient with multiple chronic conditions, which are different from the needs of a high-utilizer patient with a complex social-determinants profile, which are different from the needs of a post-discharge patient in their first 30 days at home, which are different from the needs of a pregnant patient navigating prenatal care. Most institutional deployments either start with a specific population (post-discharge is a common first deployment, given the well-documented readmission risk in the post-discharge window) and expand, or run multiple population-specific instances of the same underlying architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing care-coordination software, particularly when it provides direct guidance about care decisions, prior auth strategy, or specialist selection, can sit on or near the FDA Software-as-a-Medical-Device line depending on the specific functionality. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's 2022 final guidance on Clinical Decision Support software addresses the regulatory positioning of patient-facing decision-support software; the boundary between coordination work (administrative) and care-decision support (potentially regulated) depends on the specific recommendations the software produces --> The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design through ongoing post-market surveillance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters, not sprints. The integration work is the dominant cost; the conversational core is the smaller part. The institutional integration with the EHR, with referral systems, with prior-auth systems, with scheduling systems across multiple practice settings, with hospital discharge systems, with post-acute care facilities, with home health, with durable medical equipment, with pharmacy, with social services, with care-management workflows, and with community resources is multi-quarter work, with named operational ownership and material institutional change-management investment. Institutions building this expecting a fast time-to-value are usually disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the assistant's value is not in the conversational interface. The value is in the coordination work the assistant can actually accomplish on the patient's behalf, which depends almost entirely on the integration depth and the human-care-management backstop. A coordination assistant with a beautiful conversational interface and shallow integrations is a dressed-up FAQ bot that frustrates patients when it cannot actually help. A coordination assistant with deep integrations and a competent human backstop is, for the right patient population at the right time in their care journey, one of the highest-leverage tools in the institutional patient-engagement portfolio. The order in which you do the work matters. Build the integration spine first, then the conversational layer on top of it; do not build the conversational layer first and try to retrofit integrations later.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
