[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Longitudinal Multi-System Care Coordination Grounded In Care Plans, Loop-Closing Discipline, and Human Backstop
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Been a Human-Labor Problem For So Long
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-spreadsheet problem for almost all of its history. The reason is structural. Care coordination requires holding a longitudinal model of the patient's care across multiple entities, each of which uses different systems, different terminologies, different operational processes, and different incentives. The PCP's office uses one EHR; the orthopedist's office uses a different EHR; the imaging center uses a third system; the pharmacy uses a different platform entirely; the home health agency uses something else; the post-acute care facility uses something else again; the durable medical equipment supplier has their own portal; the insurance company has their own member-services system; the payer's prior auth queue is in a different system from the payer's claims-status system; the community resource (a transportation service, a food bank, a county health-department program) uses whatever they happen to use, which is often a phone number, a website, and a paper intake form.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The work of coordination, as nurses and care managers have done it for decades, is the work of pulling each of these threads, knowing where each one is, knowing what the next step is supposed to be, knowing who is responsible, and following up when something stalls. The cognitive load of this work is enormous. A care manager carrying a panel of 100 patients with active care plans is keeping, in her head and in her notes, hundreds of pending items distributed across hundreds of entities, each of which has its own pace and its own failure modes. The work scales linearly with panel size and approximately linearly with the complexity of each patient's care. The reason institutional care management programs reach a single-digit percent of attributed lives is not that the work is unimportant; it is that the work is bounded by what a human care manager can carry, and the math does not work for the broad population.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital coordination tools, roughly the late 2000s through the late 2010s, tried to address this with referral-management portals, patient portals, and care-plan trackers. The portals improved visibility for the people who logged in, but they did not actually do coordination work. The portal could show that a referral had been placed; the portal could not call the orthopedist's office and confirm that the referral had been received and ask when the patient would be scheduled. The portal could show a list of pending preventive-care items; the portal could not place the orders, schedule the appointments, and follow up if the patient did not show. The patient was still the coordinator; the portal was just the dashboard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2018 to 2023, layered automation on top of the portals: rules-based reminder engines, automated outreach campaigns, scheduling integrations, integration with EHRs through HL7 v2, X12, and (increasingly) FHIR APIs. These tools improved automation for specific high-volume workflows (mass appointment-reminder campaigns, lab-recall outreach, prior-auth submission for specific common procedures), but they were not flexible enough to handle the long tail of coordination work. The patient with seventeen pending items across six entities was still doing the coordination work; the automation handled only a few of the seventeen items, and the remaining items were still on the patient's spreadsheet (or, more typically, in the patient's head, slowly being forgotten).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can hold a sustained, contextual conversation grounded in a structured care plan, that can reason about what is supposed to happen next based on the institutional clinical-coordination guidelines, and that can drive coordination work through a tool surface that touches the actual systems where the work needs to happen. A conversational coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can hold the longitudinal model that the human care manager would carry (the care plan, the referrals, the prior auths, the recent interactions, the open items, the patient's stated preferences and concerns), can engage in the kinds of focused coordination conversations a care manager would have with the patient, can drive structured tool-calls that actually advance the work (looking up a referral status, requesting a prior-auth-status check, surfacing care-gap recommendations, generating outreach to a specialist's office, scheduling appointments through institutional booking infrastructure), can apply the institution's coordination playbook in a way that is calibrated to the individual patient, can scale to the broad population that human care management cannot reach, and can escalate to the human team when escalation is warranted. The LLM is not a care manager. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the institutional care-coordination workflow operate at population scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "view-and-message" to "ask-and-act." The assistant's value is concentrated in three places: the longitudinal coordination memory (holding the patient's complete coordination state and surfacing it on demand), the loop-closing tool surface (actually advancing the coordination work, not just visualizing it), and the operational reach (extending the care management team's effective coverage from a few percent of the population to the broad multi-condition majority).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active conditions, current care plan, current care team, current open coordination items including referrals and prior auths and pending preventive care, recent encounter history, recent conversation history, the patient's stated preferences), access to a structured library of institutional coordination playbooks (post-discharge sequences, multi-specialist orchestration patterns, common referral pathways, prior-auth strategies, common social-determinants pathways), and a careful set of tools for retrieving care-plan items, retrieving referral and prior-auth status, surfacing care gaps, scheduling appointments, generating outreach to specialist offices, requesting transportation, requesting durable-medical-equipment, looking up community resources, and escalating to the human care management team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes, sometimes initiated by the patient (the most common pattern, particularly for "where is this," "what is supposed to happen next," and "I need help with this" interactions), sometimes initiated by the assistant per a care-plan milestone (a post-discharge follow-up window opens, a referral is overdue for closure, a preventive-care item is due, a prior auth is approaching expiration), sometimes triggered by an upstream event (the orthopedist's office sent back a status update on a referral; the prior auth came back denied; the discharge summary came in from the hospital; the post-acute facility flagged a clinical change), sometimes triggered by a care-team event (the human care manager flags a coordination item that needs patient engagement).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and care-plan introduction.** The patient is enrolled in the coordination program by their care team or by the institution's automated enrollment logic (typical patterns include post-discharge enrollment, multi-condition complexity-driven enrollment, and high-utilizer enrollment). The first conversation introduces the assistant, sets expectations, captures any patient-stated preferences, and walks the patient through the current open coordination items so the patient knows what the assistant is tracking and can correct anything that is wrong from the patient's perspective.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated coordination conversations.** The patient asks "where is my orthopedic referral," "what is supposed to happen next with my care," "I need help getting transportation to my specialist appointment," "what do I do about this denied prior auth," "is the home health visit scheduled yet," "I'm overwhelmed by all the things on my list, can someone help me prioritize," and the assistant answers within scope using grounded retrieval over the patient's actual coordination state and the institution's coordination playbook, taking action through the tool surface where action is appropriate, and escalating outside scope or where action requires human judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Assistant-initiated coordination conversations, with care.** The assistant initiates conversations at care-plan milestones (a referral that has been open for ten days without acceptance; a prior auth approaching expiration; a post-discharge follow-up window opening; a preventive-care item that is due; a stuck transition-of-care item). The cadence is deliberately conservative; care coordination conversations are surveillance-flavored if too frequent, and engagement attrition is the central operational risk. The institutional engagement-policy specifies maximum cadence per patient with explicit opt-out granularity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Loop-closing on referrals.** The assistant tracks referrals across the loop: placed, accepted, scheduled, completed, results back, plan updated. At each stage, the assistant knows what the next step is supposed to be, who is responsible, and what to do if the next step does not happen on time. When a referral is stuck, the assistant either drives the next step through the tool surface (e.g., generating outreach to the specialist's office to confirm receipt) or escalates to a human care navigator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-transition orchestration.** Care transitions (hospital discharge to home, post-acute facility to home, primary care to specialist, specialist to specialist, ED visit to primary care follow-up) are the highest-risk windows in the patient's care journey. <!-- TODO: verify; the readmission-risk window in the first 30 days post-discharge is well-documented in CMS readmissions data, with specific 30-day all-cause readmission rates varying by condition and population --> The assistant runs structured transition-of-care sequences: pre-transition preparation, transition-day touchpoint, day-1, day-3, day-7, day-14, day-30 touchpoints with specific clinical and coordination questions at each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-auth navigation.** Prior auths are one of the most common sources of patient frustration and care delay in U.S. healthcare. <!-- TODO: verify; the AMA, the AHA, and patient-advocacy organizations have published extensively on prior-auth burden, denials, and delays; specific figures and policy implications continue to evolve including the 2024 CMS prior-authorization final rule --> The assistant tracks prior auth status, helps the patient understand what is needed, surfaces where the prior auth is in the process, drives the next step where appropriate (e.g., reminding the prescriber's office to submit additional clinical documentation, generating outreach to the payer for status), and escalates to a human care navigator for denied prior auths or stuck cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-gap surfacing and closure.** The patient is overdue for preventive care: a mammogram, a colonoscopy, a flu vaccine, a diabetic eye exam, a foot exam, a bone density scan, a depression screening, an annual wellness visit. The assistant surfaces the gaps, explains them in plain language, drives scheduling where the integration permits, and escalates the patient to the appropriate care-team member where additional clinical context is needed (e.g., shared-decision-making for cancer screening).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Specialist-coordination orchestration.** The patient is seeing endocrinology for diabetes, cardiology for hypertension and afib, nephrology for chronic kidney disease, ophthalmology for diabetic retinopathy screening, and primary care for everything else. The assistant helps the patient understand what each is doing, what the relationships are between the specialists, where the open items are, and how to think about the coordination across them. The assistant does not invent the coordination plan; the coordination plan is part of the patient's care plan, authored by the clinical team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Ancillary-service coordination.** The patient needs transportation to a specialist appointment, durable medical equipment after a procedure, home health for post-discharge wound care, home oxygen for COPD, infusion services for chemotherapy, social services for food insecurity. The assistant runs the coordination work for these ancillary services through the institution's existing infrastructure, with appropriate handoffs to the human care navigation team for cases that need clinical judgment or institutional advocacy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants navigation.** The patient is food-insecure, housing-insecure, transportation-insecure, lacks access to consistent caregiving support, has language-access needs, has disability-access needs. The assistant routes to the institution's social-services pathways, to community resources, and (for high-acuity social-determinants concerns) to a human community-health-worker.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-empowerment support.** The patient asks "what should I be tracking myself," "what should I expect at this specialist visit," "what questions should I ask my doctor at my next appointment," "what should I do if X happens between now and my next appointment," "how do I read this lab result." The assistant answers within scope using grounded retrieval over the institution's patient-education content and the patient's actual care-plan context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warm-handoff to human care management.** The assistant escalates to a human care navigator (or, for higher-acuity cases, to a registered nurse care manager or social worker) when the situation calls for one: any case where the next step requires institutional advocacy with another entity (the orthopedist's office is not returning the referral; the prior auth was denied and the patient needs help with the appeal); any case where the patient is distressed, overwhelmed, or in crisis; any case where the clinical judgment required exceeds the assistant's scope; any case where the patient explicitly requests a human; any case where the assistant's confidence is below the institutional threshold; any case where the situation is outside the assistant's scoped patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team reporting.** The care team has visibility into the assistant's interactions through structured reports (daily-digest of significant interactions, weekly summaries, alert events for stuck items, alert events for distressed patients). The reports are designed for the care team's workflow, not as raw conversation transcripts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term coordination memory.** The assistant maintains the longitudinal coordination state across episodes. The patient's preferences are remembered. The patient's stated personal context (life circumstances, caregiving constraints, transportation realities, language and literacy preferences, communication preferences) is remembered and surfaced at relevant moments. The assistant is not pretending to be a friend; the assistant is acting as a longitudinal coordination record that is accessible during conversations, in a way the typical chart and the typical portal cannot be.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in some coordination tips, and let it engage with patients about their care. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical and operational consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of the patient's actual coordination state.** The patient's open referrals, open prior auths, pending preventive care, scheduled and completed appointments, active care-plan items, recent encounters, and stated preferences live in the institution's actual systems. Without structured retrieval that pulls these into the conversation context, the LLM is guessing. A guess that says "your referral is probably scheduled for next week" when in fact the referral is stuck in a queue is worse than no answer; it actively misleads the patient about whether the work is being done.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of institutional referral pathways.** Referral routing depends on the patient's insurance, the patient's network, the institution's preferred specialists, the patient's geographic constraints, and many other factors that are encoded in the institution's coordination playbook. A generalist LLM does not know the institution's playbook; it improvises, and the improvisations are wrong often enough that the assistant is not safe to deploy without grounding.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of prior auth.** Prior auth is one of the most procedurally specific and operationally complex domains in healthcare administration. Each payer has its own prior-auth process, its own clinical criteria, its own appeal pathway, its own status-portal. A generalist LLM, asked about a denied prior auth, will produce confidently-wrong answers about what to do next. The assistant operates on the institution's actual prior-auth tracking system, with structured tools that know the per-payer process.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents coordination outcomes when grounding is weak.** A coordination assistant freestyling about referral statuses, prior-auth statuses, appointment statuses, or any other coordination state is a hallucination machine. The grounding discipline (retrieve the actual state from the actual system; cite the source; never invent state) is the architectural floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to drive action versus when to escalate.** Some coordination work the assistant can drive directly through tool calls (looking up a referral status, scheduling a transportation pickup, ordering durable medical equipment from a contracted vendor); some work requires human judgment and institutional advocacy (driving a stuck referral; navigating a denied prior auth; advocating with a payer; resolving a care-plan ambiguity). The assistant's escalation logic is encoded explicitly in the institutional coordination playbook; the LLM does not invent it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when not to engage.** A coordination assistant that initiates too many conversations is a surveillance-flavored bot that patients opt out of. The institutional engagement-policy specifies maximum cadence per patient, quiet hours, opt-out granularity, and engagement-fatigue-aware backoff. The policy is encoded in the engagement scheduler, not left to the LLM's discretion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has crisis-detection blind spots.** Coordination conversations frequently surface acute medical concerns ("my chest has been hurting since yesterday and I don't know what to do"), mental-health concerns ("I'm so overwhelmed I can't keep going"), social-determinants crises ("my power got cut off and my insulin needs to be refrigerated"), and abuse disclosures ("my husband doesn't want me going to my appointments anymore"). The continuous crisis-screening primitive from the previous chapter 11 recipes carries over and is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications for coordination conversations.** The conversation contains PHI distributed across multiple care entities, multi-payer information including coverage details, multiple specialists' clinical context, and (frequently) social-determinants information including disclosures with potential mandatory-reporting implications (elder abuse, intimate-partner violence, child abuse where relevant). The audit, retention, access-control, and downstream-clinical-workflow integration story has to handle each, with appropriate consent posture for cross-entity information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the patient's situation has changed materially.** A patient's coordination state can shift quickly (a new diagnosis, a new procedure scheduled, a hospitalization, a discharge, a new insurance, a new specialist added, a new comorbidity). The assistant's longitudinal state has to be refreshed as new information arrives, and the refresh has to be a deliberate architectural primitive, not an afterthought.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-entity coordination.** A coordination conversation about a stuck referral may involve the PCP's office, the specialist's office, the patient's insurance company, the institution's referral management team, and the patient's family. The assistant has to know which entity is responsible for which next step, what the institutional escalation pathway is for each, and what the appropriate language to use with the patient is. The institutional coordination playbook encodes this; the LLM does not invent it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of state-and-payer-specific coverage and process variations.** Care coordination is heavily affected by payer (Medicare, Medicare Advantage, Medicaid, commercial, exchange) and by state (state-specific Medicaid programs, state-specific consumer protection laws, state-specific prior-auth regulations). The institutional coordination playbook encodes the variations; the LLM does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has FDA-positioning implications.** Patient-facing coordination software that provides direct guidance about care decisions, specialist selection, prior-auth strategy, or care-plan deviations can sit on or near the FDA SaMD line. The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the human care manager should know.** A coordination assistant that handles a coordination interaction without the human care manager's awareness can produce care-team-bot misalignment. The institutional integration with the human care management workflow is explicit, with structured handoff and reporting at the appropriate cadence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Coordination Assistant Has to Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking (for relevant scenarios), continuous crisis screening as architectural primitive, warm-handoff infrastructure with backstop human capacity. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have at the same depth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system integration as architectural primitive.** The assistant's value is in the integrations. Referral management system, prior-auth system, scheduling systems across multiple practice settings, hospital discharge system, post-acute care facility integrations, home health, durable medical equipment, pharmacy, insurance/payer integrations, social services pathways, community resource directories. Each is a real integration with real data contracts, real failure modes, and real operational ownership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Loop-closing discipline as a core competency.** The assistant tracks coordination loops across multi-step processes (referral placed, accepted, scheduled, completed, results back, plan updated); the loop is not closed until the final step. The discipline of "what is the next step, who is responsible, what is the deadline, what happens if it does not happen on time, who needs to know" is encoded in the institutional coordination playbook and operationalized through the tool surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-episode longitudinal memory.** The chronic disease coach maintains memory within a condition over time; the coordination assistant maintains memory across multiple episodes and multiple conditions over time. A patient discharged from a hospital after a fall, who later has a heart attack, who later has cancer treatment, has three episodes that interact with each other and with the patient's underlying chronic-condition coordination. The longitudinal-store schema supports this multi-episode complexity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination-playbook-as-code with care-management-leadership ownership.** The institutional coordination playbook (post-discharge sequences, multi-specialist orchestration patterns, common referral pathways, prior-auth strategies, common transition-of-care patterns, common social-determinants pathways) is owned by care management leadership, version-controlled, reviewed annually, and signed off before adoption. The assistant operates on the playbook; the assistant does not invent coordination logic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-entity consent posture.** Care coordination involves information flowing across institutional boundaries: from the PCP to the specialist, from the hospital to the post-acute facility, from the institution to the payer, from the institution to the home health agency, and so on. The patient's consent posture for each information flow is explicit, captured at appropriate granularity, and operationally enforced through the tool surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Human care management workforce sized appropriately.** The assistant is deployed with backstop human care management capacity (registered nurse care managers for clinical-judgment cases, social workers for social-determinants cases, community health workers for community-resource navigation, patient advocates for institutional advocacy). Capacity sized to the population and the expected escalation volume; under-sized capacity is a deployment-readiness gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-correlation pipeline as core post-launch commitment.** The assistant's clinical and operational performance is measured against actual outcomes: referral closure rate, prior auth turnaround time, care-gap closure rate, readmission rate (for post-discharge populations), ED utilization, downstream clinical outcomes (disease-specific outcomes for the relevant cohorts), patient-reported outcomes including the Press Ganey and CAHPS-style coordination questions. The outcome-correlation pipeline is a multi-quarter post-launch commitment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy alignment as architectural constraint.** Patient-facing coordination software, particularly when it provides direct guidance about care decisions or care-plan deviations, can sit on or near the FDA SaMD line. The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the previous patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration depth is the product.** A coordination assistant with shallow integrations is, functionally, a glorified FAQ bot. The patient asks "where is my referral" and the assistant has to actually know. The integration with the referral management system is not optional. The integration with the prior-auth system is not optional. The integration with the scheduling systems is not optional. Most institutions discover, partway through the project, that their integration substrate is more brittle and less complete than they expected, and that closing the integration gaps is the dominant pre-launch work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The coordination playbook investment is multi-quarter.** The institutional coordination playbook (the structured library of post-discharge sequences, multi-specialist orchestration patterns, common referral pathways, prior-auth strategies, transition-of-care patterns, social-determinants pathways) is reviewed, version-controlled, and signed off by care management leadership. Most institutions discover that what their care managers do well is not formally written down anywhere, and that codifying it is genuinely valuable clinical work that should have been done years ago.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Engagement attrition is the central operational risk and has coordination-specific drivers.** Patients with complex care coordination needs are often the patients with the lowest digital comfort, the highest cognitive load, the most competing demands on their attention, and the most reasons to give up on yet another tool that promised to help and did not. Engagement-quality engineering, channel-mix design, cadence calibration, content-relevance tuning, and conversation-quality review all exist primarily to address attrition. The assistant that tries to do too much, surfaces too many open items at once, or initiates too many conversations is the assistant that gets opted out of.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-empowerment-versus-paternalism calibration is genuinely hard.** A coordination assistant that tells the patient what to do every step of the way is paternalistic and erodes the patient's sense of agency. A coordination assistant that surfaces information without helping the patient act on it is leaving the patient where they were. The calibration between supporting the patient's agency and actually doing coordination work on the patient's behalf is, in part, a conversational-design discipline (asking what the patient wants, offering rather than directing, supporting rather than substituting), and in part a tool-design discipline (giving the patient the option to drive coordination themselves with tool support, the option to delegate to the assistant, or the option to delegate to a human care navigator).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are not optional.** Care coordination needs are uneven across populations; the populations with the highest coordination burden (older adults with multiple chronic conditions, immigrant populations navigating an unfamiliar system, populations with limited English proficiency, populations with limited digital comfort) are often the populations with the highest unmet need and the most potential for coordination interventions to improve outcomes. <!-- TODO: verify; disparities in care coordination outcomes by demographics including race, ethnicity, language, age, and socioeconomic status are documented in the public-health and health-services-research literature; specific figures vary by condition, intervention, and population --> A coordination assistant that operates only in English, only references mainstream care pathways, and only delivers content at one reading level is excluding much of the population it should be serving.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants-of-health context is a coordination reality.** A patient cannot follow through on a specialist referral if they cannot get transportation. A patient cannot take a prescribed medication if they cannot afford it. A patient cannot do post-discharge wound care at home if they do not have running water. The assistant's coordination work is partially clinical and partially logistical; the logistical work is heavily affected by social determinants. Mitigation: integration with the institution's social-services pathways, with community resources, with transportation services, with food-insecurity programs, with housing-stability resources; warm-handoff to a community health worker or social worker for high-acuity social-determinants cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver involvement is the rule, not the exception.** Patients with complex care coordination needs frequently have a caregiver (a daughter, a son, a spouse, a paid caregiver, a friend) who is, in practice, doing some or all of the coordination work. The assistant's design has to accommodate caregiver participation, with appropriate consent posture, identity verification, and access controls. Patient-portal-with-proxy-access patterns extend; the assistant respects them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient population is heterogeneous, more so than for any other recipe in this chapter.** A patient post-discharge has different needs from a patient mid-cancer-treatment, who has different needs from a patient with multiple chronic conditions in stable management, who has different needs from a high-utilizer patient with complex social determinants, who has different needs from a pregnant patient navigating prenatal care. Most institutional deployments either start with a specific population and expand or run multiple population-specific instances of the same architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-coach integration is a specific architectural and operational discipline.** The human care management team has to trust the assistant, has to know when to expect alerts, has to have efficient tooling for reviewing the assistant's interactions, and has to have a feedback path for playbook revision. Building this without the care management team's active involvement produces an assistant the care team does not use, which is an expensive failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regulatory positioning depends on the specific functionality.** An assistant that surfaces appointment status and helps the patient schedule appointments is administrative software. An assistant that recommends specific specialists, suggests care-plan deviations, or provides guidance on prior-auth appeal strategy is closer to the regulated boundary. Mitigation: scope discipline that is tight on the regulated side (the assistant operates on the patient's signed care plan; the assistant does not invent care recommendations; the assistant routes care-decision questions to the care team).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-payer complexity affects what is and is not in scope.** A coordination assistant for a Medicare Advantage population operates with a different prior-auth landscape, network, and benefits structure than an assistant for a Medicaid population, which is different from a commercial population, which is different from a self-pay population. Mitigation: per-payer playbook variations encoded in the coordination playbook; per-payer tool-surface variations where appropriate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Interoperability is a moving target.** The 21st Century Cures Act and the ONC's interoperability rule have changed the data-availability landscape substantially since 2020, with USCDI v3 expanding the standardized data classes and FHIR APIs becoming the dominant integration pattern. <!-- TODO: verify; the 21st Century Cures Act, the ONC's information blocking rule, and USCDI versioning are documented in HHS regulatory publications; specific provisions and timelines have continued to evolve --> Coordination integrations that are FHIR-native are easier to build and maintain; coordination integrations that depend on legacy HL7 v2, X12, or proprietary APIs are expensive to maintain. Mitigation: prefer FHIR where available; isolate legacy integrations behind anti-corruption layers; budget for ongoing integration-maintenance work.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organizational data sharing is governed by complex consent and information-blocking considerations.** When the patient's care involves multiple organizations (a hospital plus a primary care practice plus a specialist plus a payer), data sharing is governed by HIPAA, by the information-blocking rule, by state-specific consent laws, and (for substance-use treatment information) by 42 CFR Part 2. The assistant's data-handling posture is reviewed by counsel familiar with the multi-organizational data-sharing landscape.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-native integrations are increasingly available.** USCDI v3 and the ONC's interoperability rule have expanded the FHIR-API surface available from major EHRs and from major payers. <!-- TODO: verify; USCDI versioning, ONC certification requirements, and major-EHR FHIR API maturity have continued to evolve; specific data-class availability varies by EHR and by payer --> Coordination integrations built on FHIR are easier to construct, easier to extend, and easier to maintain than legacy integrations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Da Vinci HRex and CRD profiles support coordination-specific workflows.** The HL7 Da Vinci project has published implementation guides for coverage-requirements-discovery (CRD), documentation-templates-and-rules (DTR), prior-auth-support (PAS), payer-data-exchange (PDex), and other coordination-relevant workflows. <!-- TODO: verify; the Da Vinci project's implementation guides have continued to evolve with payer and provider adoption varying by use case and region --> Where these are operationalized in the institution's payer relationships, they substantially reduce the integration-and-workflow burden.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA is operational and expanding.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement (TEFCA) launched in late 2023 with multiple Qualified Health Information Networks (QHINs) facilitating cross-organizational data exchange under a common framework. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA's operational status, the number of designated QHINs, and the use cases supported have continued to evolve since the December 2023 designations --> Where the institution is connected to a QHIN, cross-organizational coordination data is increasingly accessible.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle coordination workflows well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps directly to coordination work. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve referral status, retrieve prior-auth status, schedule appointments, generate outreach to specialists, request transportation, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid assistant-plus-human-care-management is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: the assistant handles routine coordination work for the broad population, with human care management availability for high-complexity cases, escalations, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the assistant handles the high-volume routine touches while the human team focuses where their judgment is most valuable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Value-based care contracts have shifted the coordination economics.** Under fee-for-service, care coordination was a cost without a clear revenue line. Under value-based contracts (Medicare Advantage capitation, Medicare Shared Savings Program, commercial capitation, episode bundles), care coordination directly affects financial performance through avoided utilization, improved quality scores, and improved member satisfaction. <!-- TODO: verify; the financial economics of care coordination under value-based payment are documented in CMS, AHIP, and value-based care commentary; specific ROI figures vary by program and population --> Institutions in capitated arrangements have stronger business cases for coordination investment than institutions in pure fee-for-service.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several care-coordination platform vendors operate at health-system and health-plan scale, with referral management, prior-auth automation, post-discharge sequencing, care-gap surfacing, and (increasingly) AI-assisted coordination. Most major institutions run a hybrid: build a thin coordination-orchestration layer on the institution's preferred infrastructure, partner with vendors for specific integration substrates and for the human care management workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity and disparity considerations are central.** Care coordination interventions, when not designed with equity in mind, can widen disparities by disproportionately serving the already-engaged. <!-- TODO: verify; equity considerations in digital care coordination are documented in studies including those from the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine; specific figures vary by intervention and population --> Per-cohort monitoring is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
